## Summary

Implemented full vault trust-boundary + lazy-retrieval pipeline (6 units, 10 commits, 179 tests): pointer injection modes (eager/lazy), sanctioned CLI accessors with envelope-based provenance, ask-gated sensitive reads, minimized+rotated access logging, deny rules via `.claude/settings.json`, and R2a self-test. TDD workflow. Post-implementation ce:review surfaced 41 findings; 3 P0s (symlink laundering, TOCTOU, bounded-excerpt bypass) + 10 critical P1s were fixed in focused commits. Tests pass; lint clean; ready for PR (blocked on session-manifest landing first).

## Extraction Candidates

- **path-safety primitives** (concept) — realpath containment, symlink guards, scope-dir hijack detection; foundation for security boundaries across Cairn
- **envelope contract** (entity) — length-prefixed, versioned, schema-validated transport for provenance + metadata; reusable for future manifest/session structs
- **inject modes pattern** (concept) — eager (SessionStart overhead, always available) vs lazy (cold-start silent, opt-in via config); tradeoff: observability vs performance
- **access-log minimization** (concept) — hashed query, length only (never plaintext), rotated 2x with padding; audit without data leakage
- **ask-gating for sensitive reads** (concept) — `--approve` flag + `CAIRN_APPROVE=1` env; agents require explicit opt-in for raw/session access
